A yearly subscription is refundable within 14 days of purchase and includes a 365-day membership. Crucially, it was the first time since early January the unit broke below the R14.50 technical resistance mark seen as a buy-target by traders. “The Rand’s path through least resistance has been a much-discussed topic over the past few months with flows by exporters dominating and international investors stuck with piles of free money, which needs to find a high-yielding home,” said Standard Bank’s chief trader Warrick Butler. “This is not going to change until we either get a diabolical budget from Mboweni (unlikely) or there is a global black swan event which throws us a curve ball.” Last week, South Africa recorded a better-than-expected expansion in industrial production, up 1.8% in December, while mining output also inched up, suggesting faster economic momentum in 2021 following the coronavirus-induced contraction in 2020. Finance Minister Tito Mboweni is set to deliver the 2021 budget on February 24, showing better-than-forecast revenue collection. South African assets often rally in the weeks ahead of the budget, falling thereafter, according to analysts. The rand is up around 1% year-to-date against the dollar. Bonds were flat, with the yield on benchmark 10-year government issue steady at 8.520%